[2
Date: 14 Sep 98 10:53:44 EDT
From: William A. Alto <William.A.Alto@Dartmouth.EDU>

Yaws has been endemic in areas of PNG for years including Madang, New
Britian, Solomon Is, and Milne Bay Provinces. Reports of yaws in Milne Bay
go back to 1935 when 54 cases were reported from Samarai Is. Mass treatment
campaigns in the 1950s were unable to reach are areas of the colony, some
areas had not yet been explored. Yaws became a reportable disease in 1969.
One case was reported from Milne Bay between 1974 to 1979. The disease
was probably kept in check by the practice of treating respiratory
infections and otitis media with daily doses of injectable penicillin. In
the mid 1980s a resurgence of yaws was reported from Kar Kar Is (Madang)
and N. Kiriwina Is (Milne Bay). With the recent decline in rural health
services it is no surprise that the disease is again being seen with some
frequency in other areas of the country.
--
William Alto
Maine Dartmouth Family Practice
(Former Asst. Sec. Health Southern Highlands Prov, PNG)
e-mail: William.A.Alto@Dartmouth.EDU
