[3
Date: Tue, 15 Sep 1998 10:02:38 +1100 EST
From: Jo Backhouse <job@CIDM.WSAHS.NSW.GOV.AU>

Having spent some time in PNG working with yaws, allow me to correct some
of the statements quoted from the PNG paper the National. Foremost there is
some confusion between the mode of transmission of Treponema pallidum subsp
pertenue, the causative organism of yaws and T. pallidum subsp pallidum the
causative organism of venereal syphilis.
Yaws is commonly a disease of childhood; children of 2-15 years being the
reservoir for infection. Infection being nonvenereal, through abrasions
coming in direct contact with the exudate of early yaws lesions which is
teeming with treponemes. It is not considered to be a fatal disease,
however, ulceration and secondary infection by other bacteria does occur.
Vertical transmission through the mother at birth occurs with T. pallidum
sub sp pallidum (congenital syphilis) however this is not so with T.
pallidum subsp pertenue. In fact, neonates and young infants, who are often
carried in bilums for up to 4 years of age, are rarely seen with yaws. It
is when they hit the ground in bare feet so to speak that the potential for
infection arises.
Yaws affects skin, cartilage and bone. Neurological complications arising
from yaws have not been documented and certainly not blindness. The late
complications are more tissue destruction which can lead to gross facial
disfiguration (gangosa), loss of toes and foot deformity as result of
ulceration and osteoperiostitis and finally bowing of the tibia (sabre
tibia) also from osteoperiostitis.
All pathogenic treponemes are sensitive to penicillin which must be long
acting or administered over a long period to maintain a treponemicidal
level in the blood. However, as yaws is capable of periods of latency
followed by relapse with infectious lesions, treatment should be aimed at
controlling the spread of the disease. Therefore not only the patient
should receive treatment, but at least family and other close contacts.
--
Josephine L. Backhouse
Department of Clinical Microbiology
Institute of Clinical Pathology and Medical Research
Westmead Hospital
Westmead NSW 2145
Australia
